0":"1340","1283":"1283","1270":"1270","ABT 1270":"about 1270","Tythegston, Glamorgan, Wales":"Tythegston, Glamorgan, Wales","Llandudwg, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Tythegston, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Turberville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name, probably from Thouberville (Eure), or possibly from Trubleville (Seine-Maritime), both in France. The two may have been confused in surname usage."],"variants":[{"name":"Torbet","meanings":["Scottish:","from the Anglo-Norman and Middle English personal name <i>T(h)urbert</i>, <i>T(h)orbert</i>, a hybrid of Old Norse <i>Thorr</i> ‘Thor’, the name of the god of thunder, + ancient Germanic <i>-berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. The name was probably formed on the Continent; see   Turberville  .","perhaps in some cases a nickname from Old French and Middle English <i>turbot</i>, <i>turbut</i> ‘turbot’, for someone who caught or sold or resembled this fish."]},{"name":"Turbyfill","meanings":["Altered form of English   Turberville  ."]},{"name":"Tuberville","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Turberville  . This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Turville","meanings":["English (Surrey and Hampshire; of Norman origin):","habitational name from Tourville‐la‐Campagne (Eure, France). The placename derives from the Old Norse personal name <i>Thórr</i> + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘farmstead, estate’ (from Latin <i>villa</i>).","occasionally a shortened form of   Turberville  ."]},{"name":"Turbeville","meanings":["English: variant of   Turberville  ."]},{"name":"Troublefield","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Turberville  ."]}]},{"name":"Wilcock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): from the Middle English personal name <i>Wilcoc</i>, a pet form of   William   (composed of the elements   Will   1 + the hypocoristic suffix <i>-cok</i>; see   Cocke  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Willcoxon","meanings":["English: patronymic from   Wilcock  ."]},{"name":"Wilcockson","meanings":["English (Derbyshire and Nottinghamshire): patronymic meaning ‘son of   Wilcock  ’."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]},{"name":"Wilcott","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): habitational name from Willicote in Clifford Chambers (Gloucestershire). The placename derives from Old English <i>wilig</i> ‘willow’ + <i>cot</i> ‘cottage, hut, shelter’. In some cases perhaps an altered form of   Wilcock  ."]},{"name":"Wilcox","meanings":["English (Yorkshire, Lancashire, and Flintshire): variant of   Wilcock  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This form of the surname is based on the pronunciation."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Wilcock Turberville was born about 1270, in Tythegston, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Richard de Turberville, was 36 and his mother, Annes Roger, was 42. He had at least 1 son with Mawd verch Hopkin."},"et":{"ABT 1270–":"umbes 1270–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1283–1340":"1283–1340","1235–1283":"1235–1283","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","about 1283":"umbes 1283","1235":"1235","1230":"1230","1340":"1340","1283":"1283","1270":"1270","AB